<Layout title="🍞 Kura 2026 — Indexed Graded Monads">
  <main>

    <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to index</a>

    <h1>Indexed Graded Monads and Their Logics</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Kura, Gaboardi, Sekiyama, Unno · ESOP 2026 · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.14846"><img src="/natural-breadcrumbs/arxiv.webp" alt="arxiv" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/> arXiv:2601.14846</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/staton-2025/">🍞 Staton 2025</a> (Hoare triples), <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/gaboardi-2021/">🍞 Gaboardi 2021</a> (graded effects). 10 min total.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">An <strong>indexed graded monad</strong> combines two ideas: the <em>index</em> says which type of state you start and end in (like a state machine), and the <em>grade</em> tracks cumulative effects. Definition 7 gives the composition rule: the output index of stage 1 must equal the input index of stage 2.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Indexing = state machine -->
    <h3>Indexing — which state you're in</h3>
    <p>An indexed monad T(i, j, A) means: "a computation that starts in state i, ends in state j, and produces a value of type A." You can only compose T(i, j, _) with T(j, k, _) — the output state of the first must match the input state of the second. This is the handshake.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Indexed computation: (start-state end-state value)
; Compose only when indices match: T(i,j) ; T(j,k) = T(i,k)

(define (make-indexed start end val) (list start end val))
(define idx-start car)
(define idx-end cadr)
(define idx-val caddr)

(define (idx-bind m f)
  (let* ((j (idx-end m))
         (result (f (idx-val m))))
    (if (eq? j (idx-start result))
        (make-indexed (idx-start m) (idx-end result) (idx-val result))
        (error "Index mismatch — handshake failed"))))

; raw -> filtered -> ranked
(define step1 (make-indexed 'raw 'filtered '(a b c)))
(define step2-fn (lambda (v) (make-indexed 'filtered 'ranked (length v))))

(define pipeline (idx-bind step1 step2-fn))
(display "pipeline: ") (display pipeline) (newline)
; (raw ranked 3) — indices chain, handshake holds
`} />

    <details class="my-2">
      <summary class="text-xs text-gray-500 cursor-pointer">imperative equivalent</summary>
      <Repl client:load initialCode={`# Indexed computation in Python
class Indexed:
    def __init__(self, start, end, val):
        self.start, self.end, self.val = start, end, val

    def bind(self, f):
        result = f(self.val)
        assert self.end == result.start, f"Index mismatch: {self.end} != {result.start}"
        return Indexed(self.start, result.end, result.val)

    def __repr__(self):
        return f"({self.start} -> {self.end}: {self.val})"

step1 = Indexed("raw", "filtered", ["a", "b", "c"])
step2 = lambda v: Indexed("filtered", "ranked", len(v))

print(step1.bind(step2))
`} />
    </details>

    <!-- 2. Grading on top -->
    <h3>Adding grades — indexed AND graded</h3>
    <p>Now add a grade: T(i, j, e, A) means "start in i, end in j, with effect e, producing A." Composition requires index match (handshake) AND grade composition (budget accounting). This is Definition 3 in the paper.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Indexed graded computation: (start end grade value)
(define (make-ig s e g v) (list s e g v))
(define ig-start car)
(define ig-end cadr)
(define ig-grade caddr)
(define ig-val cadddr)

(define (ig-bind m f grade-op)
  (let* ((j (ig-end m))
         (result (f (ig-val m))))
    (if (eq? j (ig-start result))
        (make-ig (ig-start m)
                 (ig-end result)
                 (grade-op (ig-grade m) (ig-grade result))
                 (ig-val result))
        (error "Index mismatch"))))

; stage 1: raw->cached, cost 2
(define step1 (make-ig 'raw 'cached 2 '(x y z)))

; stage 2: cached->filtered, cost 1
(define step2-fn
  (lambda (v) (make-ig 'cached 'filtered 1 (length v))))

(define result (ig-bind step1 step2-fn +))
(display "result: ") (display result) (newline)
; (raw filtered 3 3) — indices chain, grades add
`} />

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Confidence: <strong class="text-green-400">Simplified.</strong> Grades are integers, not elements of a preordered semiring. Same composition structure.</p>

    <!-- 3. Restricted pointwise order -->
    <h3>The restricted pointwise order</h3>
    <p>Kura's key innovation: the <strong>restricted pointwise order</strong> on graded predicates. A graded predicate Q at grade e refines Q' at grade e' if e ≤ e' and Q(x) implies Q'(x) for all x. This lets you weaken postconditions by increasing the allowed effect budget — you can always over-approximate.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Restricted pointwise order:
; (Q, e) ≤ (Q', e') iff e ≤ e' AND Q(x) => Q'(x) for all x
; "Tighter postcondition at lower cost refines looser at higher cost"

(define (refines? Q e Q-prime e-prime test-vals)
  (and (<= e e-prime)
       (every (lambda (x)
         (if (Q x) (Q-prime x) #t))
       test-vals)))

(define Q  (lambda (x) (> x 10)))     ; strong: x > 10
(define Q* (lambda (x) (> x 0)))      ; weak: x > 0

(define test-vals '(-5 0 5 10 15 20))

(display "(x>10, cost=1) refines (x>0, cost=3)? ")
(display (refines? Q 1 Q* 3 test-vals)) (newline)
; #t — tighter postcondition, lower budget

(display "(x>0, cost=3) refines (x>10, cost=1)? ")
(display (refines? Q* 3 Q 1 test-vals)) (newline)
; #f — looser postcondition can't refine tighter
`} />

    <!-- 4. The handshake (Def 7) -->
    <h3>The handshake — Definition 7</h3>
    <p>Definition 7 gives the composition rule for indexed graded Hoare triples. If <code>{'{P}'} c₁ : (i→j, e₁) {'{R}'}</code> and <code>{'{R}'} c₂ : (j→k, e₂) {'{Q}'}</code>, then <code>{'{P}'} c₁;c₂ : (i→k, e₁·e₂) {'{Q}'}</code>. The intermediate R is the handshake — it must satisfy both the postcondition of c₁ and the precondition of c₂, at matching index j.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Definition 7: The indexed graded handshake
; {P} c1 : (i->j, e1) {R}  and  {R} c2 : (j->k, e2) {Q}
;   => {P} c1;c2 : (i->k, e1*e2) {Q}

(define (triple name pre post start end grade fn)
  (list name pre post start end grade fn))

(define (compose-triples t1 t2 grade-op)
  (let ((j1 (list-ref t1 4))
        (j2 (list-ref t2 3)))
    (if (eq? j1 j2)
        (list 'composed
              (list-ref t1 1)  ; P from t1
              (list-ref t2 2)  ; Q from t2
              (list-ref t1 3)  ; i from t1
              (list-ref t2 4)  ; k from t2
              (grade-op (list-ref t1 5) (list-ref t2 5))
              (lambda (x) ((list-ref t2 6) ((list-ref t1 6) x))))
        (error "Handshake failed: index mismatch"))))

(define t1 (triple 'stage1 'any 'valid 'raw 'cached 2 (lambda (x) (abs x))))
(define t2 (triple 'stage2 'valid 'small 'cached 'filtered 1 (lambda (x) (min x 10))))

(define result (compose-triples t1 t2 +))
(display "Composed: ") (display (list-ref result 3))
(display " -> ") (display (list-ref result 4))
(display ", grade=") (display (list-ref result 5)) (newline)
(display "Result: ") (display ((list-ref result 6) -7))
; raw -> filtered, grade=3, result=7
`} />

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Confidence: <strong class="text-green-400">Simplified.</strong> Captures the composition law. The paper's version works over graded Freyd categories with a preordered semiring.</p>

    <!-- 5. Graded monad lifting -->
    <h3>Graded monad lifting</h3>
    <p>Every indexed graded monad "lifts" predicates through the grading: if Q holds for the output, then a graded weakest-precondition wp_e(c, Q) holds for the input, adjusted by the grade. The grade tells you how much the precondition weakens.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Graded lifting: wp_e(c, Q) — weakest pre adjusted by grade
; Grade = error tolerance. Higher grade = weaker precondition.

(define (graded-wp c grade Q threshold)
  ; "Q holds for c(x) within tolerance grade"
  (lambda (x)
    (let ((result (c x)))
      (Q result))))

; Q: result is within 5 of target
(define target 100)
(define (Q-tight y) (<= (abs (- y target)) 5))
(define (Q-loose y) (<= (abs (- y target)) 20))

(define (noisy-measure x) (+ x 3))  ; systematic bias of 3

; At grade 1 (tight): wp requires x in [92, 102]
; At grade 2 (loose): wp requires x in [77, 117]
(define vals '(90 95 97 100 103 110))
(for-each (lambda (x)
  (let ((y (noisy-measure x)))
    (display x) (display " -> ") (display y)
    (display " tight:") (display (if (Q-tight y) "yes" "no"))
    (display " loose:") (display (if (Q-loose y) "yes" "no"))
    (newline)))
vals)
; Higher grade (more tolerance) => more inputs satisfy wp
`} />

